charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Hello all, I know the year has been difficult for everyone, so I thought it would be good to start 2021 with a bit of positivity and spirit, as I intend to do a fundraiser through January. My sister was diagnosed with breast cancer back in September at the age of 25, and has been going through chemotherapy during the pandemic with my family effectively isolating since September. During her treatment she has been supported by Macmillan, who have provided crucial information for her, as well as providing a network to support her if the need ever arose . My sister has shown incredible resilience, and I cannot begin to describe my pride for her, for this reason I want to support those who can actively support my sister, as well as other cancer sufferers.
I realise over the pandemic that many organised events, such as marathons and other fundraising events have not been able to go ahead, which makes supporting groups such as Macmillan more crucial than ever. 


My fundraiser challenge is to run 250km in January, which is:
•    5.9 full marathons
•    42.4 laps of Silverstone circuit
•    Further than London to Cardiff (242.6 Km)

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
There is no denying it. 2020 has been a truly terrible year. It's also been a year in which many of those in my family (blood relative or otherwise) have had their lives torn apart by a cancer diagnosis.

So, with the help of some wonderful and talented friends, I am trying to bring some christmas spirit, and raise money to support the amazing Macmillan Cancer Support.

Stille Nacht
Coventry Carol
In The Bleak Midwinter
Auld Lang Syne


Macmillan Cancer Support exists to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So please give what you can, enjoy the music, and Merry Christmas!

Credits for the music to Eavan Prenter; Oliver MacFarlane; Rosalind Peters; Michael Campbell; Joanna Clarke; Jack Hopkins and Joshua Roberts.

Thanks also to Rozzi for help with the videos, and to my mum for just being the best.

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I'm collecting vital funds for the British Heart Foundation, to power pioneering research into heart and cardiovascular diseases. The money I raise will help beat heartbreak forever. I am taking part in the Duke of Edinburgh scheme which I hope to complete in 2021, and achieve my bronze award!

I decided to choose the British Heart Foundation, as the charity I wanted to support for a number of reasons. My Grandad's mum unfortunately died from a sudden heart attack before I was born. My Grandma's Father had a heart attack when he was in his 50s but luckily lived for another 20 years. In January this year my Grandma had a double heart bypass and is recovering really well. And my Grandad has diabetes and I know that this can cause other conditions that can raise the risk for heart disease. 

As you can see the British Heart Foundation is close to my heart *excuse the pun*. I would really love to help this important charity which in turn will help others in the future.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

On Christmas Day 2020 I am planning to run a 10k and while doing so run my 1000th kilometre in 2020.  

This is not something that I set out to do, or ever thought myself capable of achieving.  When lockdown first happened in March I decided to make the most of my one hour of permitted exercise each day and see whether I could regularly run 10k in under 55 minutes.  I managed it and got hooked! 

When November's second lockdown occurred I realised that if I continued to run 2 x 10ks a week for the rest of the year I would be able to run 1000k by the end of December 2020.  I am have now reached 993k and counting...

Given how many challenges this year has brought for so many people I thought that as I was on the verge of this unexpected achievement I should also try to raise some money for a good cause. 

I have chosen the British Heart Foundation as on 1st October 1970 my grandfather Harry Mullineaux died suddenly of a heart attack aged 58. This year was the 50th anniversary of his death.  Sadly I was never able to meet Harry, but I know that he was dearly loved by all of his family, and I thought this would be a good moment to remember him.     

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people still lose their lives.

Please support me to remember Harry and all those who have lost their lives suddenly and unexpectedly and to raise money for this excellent cause.

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

eventName: GOSH London to Paris with Discover Adventure 2021
story:
Neil, Max and Patrick wanted to take on a big challenge in 2021 after getting a bit fitter during lockdown but also wanting to raise money for a charity and give back.
After hearing from a few fellow Global-e employees who were working for a charity called Radio Lollipop at Great Ormond Street, we thought combining a 350 mile cycle with a charity close to peoples hearts at the company - we were in! 
We then brought a family member (Freddie) and close friend (Archie) in to complete the team of 5 that is going take on this challenge next year and raise £8,000 for GOSH!

story:
Hi Everyone, we said a very sad farewell to a wonderful lady, Alison Rahill on Friday 11th December. and I have been inspired by her bravery to set myself a task to raise money over the next 12 months for the 2 charities “Cancer Research UK & The Roy Castle lung cancer foundation “who supported Alison Rahill through her battle with cancer.

Please see list below:

2020 Christmas Day Santa Run at Memorial Park.
2020 New Years Eve 5 Mile run around Dracote Water.
Climb the highest mountains in :
Wales, Mount Snowdon.
England, Scar Fell Pike.
Scotland, Ben Nevis.
To run the 2021 City of London Santa Run.

As some of you are aware I have a new hip, bad knee and my other hip is failing! I will complete the above without complaint so please support me to raise money in memory of such a beautiful human being Alison Rahill. I will let everyone know soon how to sponsor me over the coming months.

Sensei Andy Margaret

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Many people are still getting into difficulty around our coastlines. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. 

But during this COVID crisis fundraising is severely restricted. Our Broughty Ferry Fundraising Group was unable to organise many of our usual events last year. We had no Coffee Mornings , no Fishermans Beer Festival, no Pop Up Shop, no Christmas Carol Concert and no Street Collection. 2021 holds more uncertainty but we are aware that some of our supporters still wish to make donations. Therefore, the Virtual Contribution Box has been re-opened.

Lifeboat crews provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

We are very grateful for the donations made already and we appreciate any further contributions. Thank you.
title: RNLI Ferry Fundraisers Virtual Contribution Box 2

pageSummary: We are again offering a virtual contribution box because COVID continues to restrict our fundraising effort

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

I am doing the big winter wander to raise money for WWF to aid the programmes they participate in to help save animals and prevent extinction. I want to raise awareness of the critically endangered species they help and want to educate others on human impact on nature and the environment. 

I want to also take this opportunity to go out and photograph native British species as well as species that have been brought to Britain. I want to document them and share them with others to help them better understand the world we live in. 

At a time where the world has been rocked by the pandemic nature has had time to start to recover from the damage we have caused however this is only the start. I want more people to understand the devastating impact we have on the planet and how we can all take small steps to help save earth. 

I will hopefully be doing this walk with fellow nature lovers in a bid to raise money that will go towards the education of local communities living in close contact with the worlds most endangered animals as well as specialist equipment to monitor and track animal populations. 

Any amount is greatly appreciated. The target I’ve set is ambitious however even if I make half of it I’ll be happy that I’ve done my bit. Thank you for reading this and donating. Know you are playing your part in the global fight to save our planet.
title: Lauren 's big winter wander for WWF

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Hello - I am Darcey, I am 7 years old. I love helping people and supporting charities! I like art and swimming. I like designing things online and helping out my mum.

I really want to help other children like me in other countries, I really want them to have clean water and toilets too. I think it is important because it helps people stay healthy and keeps diseases away.

I am running 5k, although I am not very good at running, because I want to raise money for Wateraid. I have already raised some money from a quiz I did, but I would like to raise more. 

If you could sponsor me, I would be really happy. 

Plus, if we give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government.

Thank you - Darcey xxxx

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

story:
I am drinking only water this January for Wateraid.

Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water for the whole of January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Anyone who knows me will know that it'll be a tough challenge, being a bit of a (massive) sugar and caffeine addict! Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. Can you imagine not having fresh clean drinking water at the turn of a tap? It's something we all take for granted and don't even have to think about. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
